    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my civil eng midterm and im a bit stuck on materials. why do we actually need to put steel rebar inside concrete foundations? like i get that concrete is strong, but why does the steel part matter so much for the actual structure? i'm specifically confused about the difference between compressive and tensile strength in this context.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Rebar (reinforcing steel bar) is necessary in concrete foundations because it prevents cracking and breakage. When concrete is poured, it expands and contracts due to temperature changes, which can cause the concrete to break and crack. The steel rebar acts as a \"safety net,\" distributing this stress and preventing the concrete from cracking. While concrete has high compressive strength, it has relatively low tensile strength, meaning it's more prone to breaking in tension.",
